DEMONIC CONTRACTOR
Game Design Document
v1.0  |  Java + MVC  |  2D Top-Down


1. Game Overview
Demonic Contractor is a 2D top-down social strategy game where the player takes the role of a demon sent to a small gothic town to collect souls. Progress happens not through combat but through conversation. The player must identify each NPC's deepest desire and make them an offer they cannot refuse.

The game uses a dual-view system: a top-down overworld for exploration and strategy, and a first-person encounter view for dialogue — powered by the Claude AI API which plays each NPC and evaluates whether the player's pitch is convincing enough.


2. Core Game Loop
The Loop
Explore the town top-down, observe NPCs, and gather clues about their lives
Approach a house and knock — view switches to first-person encounter mode
Engage the NPC in conversation, identify their hidden desire, and pitch a deal
The AI evaluates whether the player's dialogue matches the NPC's vulnerability
If successful, the deal is struck and the town begins to change around it
Collect enough souls before the Church Investigator exposes you

Win / Lose
WIN: Reach your soul quota before the deadline set by your demonic boss
LOSE: The Church Investigator gathers enough evidence to banish you

Current build: No patrol points; a town-wide suspicion meter (0–100%) fills from deals (+18), door slams (+5), and time creep. At 100% you lose (banished). Time runs only in overworld; deadline (e.g. 10 min) without quota also loses. Win = souls ≥ quota before time runs out or suspicion maxes.


3. Dual-View System
Overworld — Top-Down
A Pokemon-style top-down map of a small gothic town. The player walks freely, observes NPC routines, and plans their approach before knocking on any door.

Element
Description
Town layout
2-3 streets, a church, a tavern, a market square, and residential homes
NPC routines
NPCs visibly move around town — market, church, neighbors, home
Visual clues
Dim lights = home, cross on door = devout, wilting garden = lonely/neglected
Time of day
Day/night cycle — some NPCs only approachable at certain times
Investigator
Visible on map — player can see and avoid him as he patrols
Ripple effects
Completed deals visually change the town — nicer house, nervous neighbor, etc.


Door Encounter — First-Person
When the player knocks on a door, the screen cuts to a first-person illustrated view. The NPC's face is visible through a door crack or window with their home partially visible behind them.

Element
Description
NPC portrait
Illustrated expressive face that reacts to the conversation in real time
Home background
Visual clues behind NPC — religious icons, messy room, family photos
Dialogue input
Player types freely — sent directly to the Claude API
Mood indicator
NPC expression shifts subtly as suspicion or warmth changes
Hellish vignette
Screen edges glow red as the NPC gets closer to accepting a deal
Exit
Player can back away at any time — NPC closes door, returns to overworld


Transitions
Knock on door -> brief animation -> hard cut to first-person encounter
Back away or door slammed -> fade out -> overworld resumes
Deal accepted -> flash effect -> NPC overworld sprite gains a subtle dark icon


